# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-aboriginal-astronomy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The second question of the 1967 Australian referendum of 27 May 1967, called by the Holt government, related to Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Voters were asked whether to give the Commonwealth Parliament the power to make special laws for Indigenous Australians, and whether Indigenous Australians should be included in official population counts for constitutional purposes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The term "the Aboriginal Race" was used in the question.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Technically the referendum question was a vote on the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginals) 1967 that would amend section 51(xxvi) and repeal section 127.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendments to the Constitution were overwhelmingly endorsed, winning 90.77% of votes cast and having majority support in all six states.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendment became law on 10 August 1967.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1901, the attorney-general, Alfred Deakin, provided a legal opinion on the meaning of section 127 of the Constitution of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 127 excluded "aboriginal natives" from being counted when reckoning the numbers of the people of the commonwealth or a state.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] His legal advice was that "half-castes" were not "aboriginal natives".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Prior to 1967, censuses asked a question about Aboriginal race to establish numbers of "half-castes" and "full-bloods".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] "Full-bloods" were then subtracted from the official population figure in accordance with the legal advice from the attorney-general.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Strong activism by individuals and both Indigenous and non-Indigenous groups greatly aided the success of the 1967 referendum in the years leading up to the vote.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Calls for Aboriginal issues to be dealt with at the federal level began as early as 1910.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From here, the overall plight of Aboriginal Australians became a fundamental political issue.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On 7 April 1965, the Menzies Cabinet decided that it would seek to repeal section 127 of the Constitution at the same time as it sought to amend the nexus provision, but made no firm plans or timetable for such action.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In August 1965, attorney-general Billy Snedden proposed to Cabinet that abolition of section 127 was inappropriate unless section 51(xxvi) was simultaneously amended to remove the words "other than the aboriginal race in any state".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] He was rebuffed, but gained agreement when he made a similar submission to the Holt Cabinet in 1966.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the meantime, his Liberal colleague Billy Wentworth had introduced a private member's bill proposing *inter alia* to amend section 51(xxvi).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1964, the Leader of the Opposition, Arthur Calwell, had proposed such a change and pledged that his party, the Australian Labor Party, would back any referendum to that effect.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In 1967, the Australian Parliament was unanimous in voting for the alteration bill.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Voters were asked to approve, together, changes to two provisions in the Constitution section 51(xxvi) and section 127.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] And the extraordinary clauses that follow (ordinarily referred to as heads of power) list most of the legislative powers of the federal parliament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The amendment gave the Commonwealth parliament power to make "special laws" with respect to Aboriginal People living in a state; the parliament already had unfettered power in regard to territories under section 122 of the Constitution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Constitution required the calculation of "the people" for several purposes in sections 24, 89, 93 and 105.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 89 related to the imposition of uniform customs duties and operated until 1901.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 93 related to uniform custom duties after being imposed by section 89 and operated until 1908.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 105 related to taking over state debts and was superseded by section 105A inserted in the Constitution in 1929 following the 1928 referendum.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Accordingly, in 1967, only section 24 in relation to the House of Representatives had any operational importance to section 127.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 24 "requires the membership of the House of Representatives to be distributed among the States in proportion to the respective numbers of their people".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The number of people in section 24 is calculated using the latest statistics of the Commonwealth which are derived from the census.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 51(xi) of the Constitution enabled the Parliament to make laws for "census and statistics" and it exercised that power to pass the *Census and Statistics Act 1905*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] At this time, territorians, while able and required to vote in elections, were not permitted to vote in referendums.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is frequently stated that the 1967 referendum gave Aboriginal people Australian citizenship and that it gave them the right to vote in federal elections; however, this was not the case.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From 1944, Aboriginal people in Western Australia could apply to become citizens of the state, which gave them various rights, including the right to vote.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This citizenship was conditional on adopting "the manner and habits of civilised life" and not associating with Aboriginal people other than their parents, siblings, children, or grandchildren, and could be taken away at any time.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Most Indigenous Australians continued to be denied the right to vote in elections for the Australian Parliament even after 1949.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The *Commonwealth Electoral Act 1962* gave all Aboriginal people the option of enrolling to vote in federal elections.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was not until the *Commonwealth Electoral Amendment Act 1983* that voting became compulsory for Aboriginal people, as it was for other Australians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Aboriginal people (and all other people) living in the Northern Territory were not allowed to vote in the referendum, which remained the case for both the Northern Territory and the Australian Capital Territory until the Constitutional amendment to section 128 after a referendum in 1977.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is also sometimes mistakenly stated that the 1967 referendum overturned a Flora and Fauna Act.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This is believed to have come from the New South Wales *National Parks and Wildlife Act* 1974, which controlled Aboriginal heritage, land and culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The other states had equivalent acts which were managed by various departments, including those relating to agriculture and fishing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Section 127 prevented the inclusion of the Indigenous Australians in the official population for constitutional purposes, i.e. their population would not be included in the calculation of the number of seats to assign for each state or in the determination of tax revenue.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The section did not prevent the Bureau of Statistics from counting or collecting other information about Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] From 1911 to 1966 the Bureau had collected information about Indigenous Australians, however this was published separately to the general population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Inclusion in the general population was thus important symbolically, but the change did not directly improve the information available to government.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Ninety percent of voters voted yes, and the overwhelming support gave the Federal Government a clear mandate to implement policies to benefit Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Many misconceptions have arisen as to the outcomes of the referendum, some as a result of it taking on a symbolic meaning during a period of increasing Aboriginal self-confidence.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was some five years before any real change occurred as a result of the referendum, but federal legislation has since been enacted covering land rights, discriminatory practices, financial assistance, and preservation of cultural heritage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It was the intention of the government and many voters that this new power was to be only used beneficially.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, in the 1998 case of *Kartinyeri v Commonwealth*, the High Court did not find that such a restriction on the power existed, with the court being split 2:2 (2 judges not deciding) as to whether or not the power could be used to the *detriment* of an identified race.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Hindmarsh Island bridge controversy and the Northern Territory Intervention are two circumstances where the post-1967 race power has arguably been used in this way.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The 1967 referendum has acquired a symbolic meaning in relation to a period of rapid social change during the 1960s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] As a result, it has been credited with initiating political and social change that was the result of other factors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The real legislative and political impact of the 1967 referendum has been to enable, and thereby compel, the federal government to take action in the area of Aboriginal Affairs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Federal governments with a broader national and international agenda have attempted to end the discriminatory practices of state governments such as Queensland and to introduce policies that encourage self-determination and financial security for Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, the effectiveness of these policies has been tempered by an unwillingness of most federal governments to deal with the difficult issues involved in tackling recalcitrant state governments.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It has been argued that Holt, who died not long after the referendum, was setting up a more extensive government response than Gorton enacted.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The benefits of the referendum began to flow to Aboriginal people in 1972.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On 26 January 1972, Aboriginal peoples erected the *Aboriginal Tent Embassy* on the lawns of the Federal Parliament building in Canberra to express their frustration at the lack of progress on land rights and racial discrimination issues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This became a major confrontation that raised Aboriginal affairs high on the political agenda in the federal election later that year.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] One week after gaining office, the Whitlam government (1972–1975) established a Royal Commission into land rights for Aboriginal people in the Northern Territory under Justice Woodward.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The recommendations were framed in terms to enable application outside the Northern Territory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The following year, the Fraser government (1975–1983) amended the Aboriginal Land (Northern Territory) Bill by introducing the Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Bill.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] This bill was passed as the *Aboriginal Land Rights Act 1976*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It is significant however that this legislation was implemented at all, given the political allegiances of the Fraser government, and shows the level of community support for social justice for Aboriginal people at the time.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Whitlam government used its constitutional powers to overrule racially discriminatory state legislation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] On reserves in Queensland, Aboriginal people were forbidden to gamble, use foul language, undertake traditional cultural practices, indulge in adultery, or drink alcohol.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] They were also required to work without payment.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the Aboriginal Courts in Queensland the same official acted as judge as well as the prosecuting counsel.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Defendants almost invariably pleaded guilty as pleas of not guilty were more than likely to lead to a longer sentence.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The Whitlam government, using the race power, enacted the *Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders (Queensland Discriminatory Laws) Act 1975* to override the state laws and eliminate racial discrimination against Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] However, no federal government ever enforced this Act.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The race power was also used by the Whitlam government to introduce affirmative action in favour of Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It established schemes whereby Aboriginal people could obtain housing, loans, emergency accommodation and tertiary education allowances.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] It also increased funding for the Aboriginal Legal Service enabling twenty-five offices to be established throughout Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The race power gained in the 1967 referendum has been used in several other pieces of significant Federal legislation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] One of the pieces of legislation enacted to protect the Gordon River catchment used the race power but applied it to all people in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The law prohibited anyone from damaging sites, relics and artefacts of Aboriginal settlement in the Gordon River catchment.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the Tasmanian Dam Case, the High Court held that even though this law applied to all people and not only to Aboriginal people, it still constituted a special law.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In the 1992 Mabo judgment, the High Court of Australia established the existence of Native Title in Australian Common Law.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] Using the race power, the Keating Government enacted the *Native Title Act 1993* and successfully defended a High Court challenge from the Queensland Government.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] In granting the Commonwealth a broad power to legislate in regards to Indigenous Australians, responsibilities for areas traditionally the purview of the states (such as housing, education and healthcare) was shared between both branches of government.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] As a result, both levels have sought to blame the other for the continuing disadvantage of Indigenous Australians, while seeking to place the cost and responsibility to manage these issues on the other.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] When John Howard's Coalition government came to power in 1996, it intervened in the Hindmarsh Island bridge controversy in South Australia with legislation that introduced an exception to the *Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Heritage Protection Act 1984*, to allow the bridge to proceed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/1967-australian-referendum-aboriginals] The High Court decided, by a majority, that the amended s.51(xxvi) of the Constitution still allowed the Commonwealth parliament to make laws either for the benefit or to the detriment of a particular race.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] The **Aboriginal Areas Protection Authority** (**AAPA**) is an independent statutory authority established under the ***Northern Territory Aboriginal Sacred Sites Act 1989***.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] Its function is to protect Aboriginal sacred sites within the Northern Territory of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] The 1989 act originated in a 1977 bill, signed into law as the *Aboriginal Sacred Sites Ordinance 1978* in November 1978, soon after the NT achieved self-government, and the **Aboriginal Sacred Sites Authority** was created.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] The legislation became a subject of controversy among developers, the Northern Territory Government and the new authority.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] Numerous amendments were proposed and debated, including its compatibility with the *Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Act 1976* (Cth), before the *Northern Territory Aboriginal Sacred Sites Act 1989* was passed on 26 May 1989, coming into force on 15 August 1989.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] This act created the Aboriginal Areas Protection Authority, which included new functions and expanded its work, and also introduced various measures to increase accountability.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] AAPA works with traditional owners to record "sites of physical, spiritual and cultural significance" on its Register of Sacred Sites.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] Prospective land developers are legally obliged to apply for an Authority Certificate through AAPA.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] It is governed by a board of 12 people, mostly senior Aboriginal custodians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-areas-protection-authority] The authority board is made up of two members appointed by the NT Government, and five male and five female Aboriginal custodians nominated by the four NT Aboriginal Land Councils.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Over 300 languages, as well as sign languages, and other groupings have developed a wide range of individual cultures.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Aboriginal art has existed for thousands of years and ranges from ancient rock art to modern watercolour landscapes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Traditional Aboriginal music developed a number of unique instruments, and contemporary Aboriginal music spans many genres.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Aboriginal peoples did not develop a system of writing before colonisation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Cultural traditions and beliefs as well as historical tellings of actual events are passed down in Aboriginal oral tradition, also known loosely as oral history (although the latter has a more specific definition).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Some of the stories are many thousands of years old.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] In a study published in February 2020, new evidence produced using radiometric dating showed that both Budj Bim and Tower Hill volcanoes erupted at least 34,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Significantly, this is a "minimum age constraint for human presence in Victoria", and also could be interpreted as evidence for the Gunditjmara oral histories which tell of volcanic eruptions being some of the oldest oral traditions in existence.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] An axe found underneath volcanic ash in 1947 was also proof that humans inhabited the region before the eruption of Tower Hill.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Australian Aboriginal art has a history spanning thousands of years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Aboriginal artists continue these traditions using both modern and traditional materials in their artworks.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Aboriginal art is the most internationally recognizable form of Australian art.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Several styles of Aboriginal art have developed in modern times including the watercolour paintings of Albert Namatjira, the Hermannsburg School, and the acrylic Papunya Tula "dot art" movement.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Painting is a large source of income for some Central Australian communities such as at Yuendumu.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Basket weaving has been traditionally practised by the women of many Aboriginal peoples across the continent for centuries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] For many Aboriginal cultures, the night sky is a repository of stories and law.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Songlines can be traced through the sky and the land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Stories and songs associated with the sky under many cultural tents.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Aboriginal Australians' oral tradition and spiritual values build on reverence for the land and on a belief in the Dreamtime, or Dreaming.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The Dreaming is considered to be both the ancient time of creation and the present-day reality of Dreaming.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] It describes the Aboriginal cosmology, and includes the ancestral stories about the supernatural creator-beings and how they created places.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Each story can be called a "Dreaming", with the whole continent criss-crossed by Dreamings or ancestral tracks, also represented by songlines.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] There are many different groups, each with their own individual culture, belief structure and language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] To Aboriginal people, some places are sacred, owing to their central place in the mythology of the local people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The words "law" and "lore" are commonly used interchangeably: "law" was introduced by the British, whereas "lore" relates to the customs and stories from the Dreamtime, which has been passed on through countless generations through songlines, stories and dance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Learned from childhood, lore dictates the rules on how to interact with the land, kinship and community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Kurdaitcha (or kurdaitcha man, and also spelled *kurdaitcha*, *gadaidja*, *cadiche*, *kadaitcha*, or *karadji*) is a type of shaman amongst the Arrernte people, an Aboriginal group in Central Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The kurdaitcha may be brought in to punish a guilty party by death.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The word may also relate to the ritual in which the death is willed by the kurdaitcha man, known also as bone-pointing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The expectation that death would result from having a bone pointed at a victim is not without foundation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Other similar rituals that cause death have been recorded around the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Victims become listless and apathetic, usually refusing food or water with death often occurring within days of being "cursed".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] When victims survive, it is assumed that the ritual was faulty in its execution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The phenomenon is recognized as psychosomatic in that death is caused by an emotional response—often fear—to some suggested outside force and is known as "voodoo death".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] As this term refers to a specific religion, the medical establishment has suggested that "self-willed death", or "bone-pointing syndrome" is more appropriate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] In Australia, the practice is still common enough that hospitals and nursing staff are trained to manage illness caused by "bad spirits" and bone pointing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The complete system of Yolngu customary law is the "Madayin", which embodies the rights and responsibilities of the owners of the law, or citizens (*rom watangu walal*, or simply *rom*).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Madayin includes the rom, as well as the objects that symbolise the law, oral rules, names and song cycles, and the sacred places that are used to maintain, develop and provide education in the law.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Rom can be roughly translated as "law" or "culture", but it embodies more than either of these words.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Galarrwuy Yunupingu has described *Rom watangu* as the overarching law of the land, which is "lasting and alive... my backbone".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] It covers ownership of land and waters and the resources within this region; it controls production trade; and includes social, religious and ethical laws.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] These include laws for conservation and farming of flora and fauna.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Observance of Madayin creates a state of balance, peace and true justice, known as *Magaya*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Rom includes bush crafts such as basket-weaving and mat-making, and stories which teach history, hunting, spear-making, gathering food, building shelters and rafts, various rituals, and taking care of others.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] "Rom" is a word and concept shared by at least one of the nearby peoples, the Anbarra, who also perform a Rom ceremony.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Ceremonies provide a time and place for everyone in the group and community to work together to ensure the ongoing survival of spiritual and cultural beliefs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Certain stories are individually "owned" by a group, and in some cases dances, body decoration and symbols in a ceremony pass on these stories only within the group, so it is vital that these ceremonies are remembered and performed correctly.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Men and women have different roles, and are sometimes appointed as guardians of a sacred site, whose role it is to care for the site and the spiritual beings who live there, achieved partly by performing ceremonies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The terms “men’s business” and “women’s business” are sometimes used; neither have greater spiritual needs or responsibilities than the other, but jointly ensure that sacred practices are passed on.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Men often conduct ceremonies, but women are also guardians of special knowledge, hold great spiritual power within a group, and conduct ceremonies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Participation in ceremonies can also be restricted by age, family group, language group, but are sometimes open to all, depending on the purpose of the ceremony.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Right of access to songs and dances pertaining to a specific ceremony belong to a certain defined group (known as manikay by the Yolngu peoples of north-east Arnhem Land, or clan songs); some may be shared with people outside the community, but some are never shared.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] There is a wide range of songs, dances, music, body ornamentation, costume, and symbolism, designed to connect the body with the spiritual world of the ancestors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Ceremonies help to sustain Aboriginal identity as well as the group's connection to country and family.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The didgeridoo originated in northern Australia, but is now used throughout the continent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Clapsticks, seed rattles and objects such as rocks or pieces of wood are used; in a few areas, women play a drum made from goanna, snake, kangaroo or emu skin.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Animal native foods include kangaroo, emu, witchetty grubs and crocodile.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Plant foods include fruits such as quandong, kutjera, spices such as lemon myrtle and vegetables such as warrigal greens, bananas and various native yams.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Since the 1970s, there has been recognition of the nutritional and gourmet value of native foods by non-Indigenous Australians, and the bushfood industry has grown enormously.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Pituri is a mixture of leaves and wood ash traditionally chewed as a stimulant (or, after extended use, a depressant) by Aboriginal Australians widely across the continent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Leaves are gathered from any of several species of native tobacco (*Nicotiana*) or from at least one distinct population of the species *Duboisia hopwoodii*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Various species of *Acacia*, *Grevillea* and *Eucalyptus* are burned to produce the ash.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Traditional healers (known as Ngangkari in the Western jester areas of Central Australia) are highly respected men and women who not only acted as healers or doctors, but also generally served as custodians of important Dreaming stories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] This "fire-stick farming", or "burning off", reduces the fuel-load for a potential major bush fire, while fertilising the ground and increasing the number of young plants, providing additional food for kangaroos and other fauna hunted for meat.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] It is regarded as good husbandry and "looking after the land" by Aboriginal people of the Northern Territory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The Australian Aboriginal languages consist of around 290–363 languages belonging to an estimated 28 language families and isolates, spoken by Aboriginal Australians of mainland Australia and a few nearby islands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The relationships between these languages are not clear at present.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Many Australian Aboriginal cultures have or traditionally had a manually coded language, a signed counterpart of their oral language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] This appears to be connected with various speech taboos between certain kin or at particular times, such as during a mourning period for women or during initiation ceremonies for men.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Avoidance speech in Australian Aboriginal languages is closely tied to elaborate tribal kinship systems in which certain relatives are considered taboo.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Avoidance relations differ from tribe to tribe in terms of strictness and to whom they apply.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Typically, there is an avoidance relationship between a man and his mother-in-law, usually between a woman and her father-in-law, and sometimes between any person and their same-sex parent-in-law.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] For some tribes, avoidance relationships are extended to other family members, such as the mother-in-law's brother in Warlpiri or cross-cousins in Dyirbal.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] All relations are classificatory – more people may fall into the "mother-in-law" category than just a man's wife's mother.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Australian Aboriginal English (AAE) is a dialect of Australian English used by a large section of the Indigenous Australian (Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander) population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Australian Kriol is an English-based creole language that developed from a pidgin used in the early days of European colonisation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The pidgin died out in most parts of the country, except in the Northern Territory, which has maintained a vibrant use of the language, spoken by about 30,000 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] It is distinct from Torres Strait Creole.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] At the point of the first colonisation, Indigenous Australians had not developed a system of writing, so the first literary accounts of Aboriginal people come from the journals of early European explorers, which contain descriptions of first contact.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] A letter to Governor Arthur Phillip written by Bennelong in 1796 is the first known work written in English by an Aboriginal person.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The Yirrkala bark petitions of 1963 are the first traditional Aboriginal document recognised by the Australian Parliament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Oodgeroo Noonuccal (1920–1993) was a famous Aboriginal poet, writer and rights activist credited with publishing the first Aboriginal book of verse: *We Are Going* (1964).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Sally Morgan's 1987 memoir *My Place* brought Indigenous stories to wider notice.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Leading Aboriginal activists Marcia Langton (*First Australians* documentary TV series, 2008) and Noel Pearson (*Up from the Mission*, 2009) are contemporary contributors to Australian non-fiction.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Other voices of Indigenous Australians include the playwright Jack Davis and Kevin Gilbert.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Writers coming to prominence in the 21st century include Kim Scott, Alexis Wright, Kate Howarth, Tara June Winch, Yvette Holt and Anita Heiss.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Aboriginal people have developed unique musical instruments and folk styles.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The didgeridoo is often considered the national instrument of Aboriginal Australians; however, it was traditionally played by peoples of Northern Australia, and only by the men.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] It has possibly been used by the people of the Kakadu region for 1500 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Clapping sticks are probably the more ubiquitous musical instrument, especially because they help maintain rhythm.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] More recently, Aboriginal musicians have branched into rock and roll, hip hop and reggae.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Bands such as No Fixed Address and Yothu Yindi were two of the earliest Aboriginal bands to gain a popular following among Australians of all cultures.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] In 1997 the State and Federal Governments set up the Aboriginal Centre for the Performing Arts (ACPA) to preserve and nurture Aboriginal music and talent across all styles and genres from traditional to contemporary.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Woggabaliri is a traditional Indigenous Australian "co-operative kicking volley game".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The Indigenous in areas of and near New South Wales played a ball game called Woggabaliri.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The ball was usually made of possum fur, and was played in a group of four to six players in circle.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] It was a co-operative kicking game to see for how long the ball can be kept in the air before it touches the ground.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The Djab Wurrung and Jardwadjali people of western Victoria once participated in the traditional game of Marn Grook, a type of football played with possum hide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The game is believed by some commentators, including Martin Flanagan, Jim Poulter and Col Hutchinson, to have inspired Tom Wills, inventor of the code of Australian rules football.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Similarity between Marn Grook and Australian football include jumping to catch the ball or high "marking", which results in a free kick.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Use of the word "mark" in the game may be influenced by the Marn Grook word *mumarki*, meaning "catch".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] However, this is likely a false etymology; the term "mark" is traditionally used in Rugby and other games that predate AFL to describe a free kick resulting from a catch, in reference to the player making a mark on the ground from which to take a free kick, rather than continuing to play on.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] There are many Indigenous AFL players at professional level, with approximately one in ten players being of Indigenous origin as of 2007.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The contribution of the Aboriginal people to the game is recognized by the annual AFL "Dreamtime at the 'G" match at the Melbourne Cricket Ground between Essendon and Richmond football clubs (the colors of the two clubs combine to form the colours of the Aboriginal flag).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Testifying to this abundance of Indigenous talent, the Aboriginal All-Stars, an AFL-level all-Aboriginal football side competes against any one of the Australian Football League's current football teams in pre-season tests.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The Clontarf Foundation and football academy is just one organisation aimed at further developing aboriginal football talent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The Tiwi Bombers began playing in the Northern Territory Football League and became the first all-Aboriginal side to compete in a major Australian competition.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Coreeda is a style of folk wrestling practiced in Australia and is based on Aboriginal combat sports that existed in the pre-colonial period before the 19th century.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] Combining the movements of the traditional kangaroo dance as a warm up ritual, with a style of wrestling that utilizes a yellow 4.5 meter diameter circle that has black and red borders (similar to the Aboriginal flag), Coreeda is often compared to sports as diverse as capoeira and sumo.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] A popular children's game in some parts of Australia is weet weet, or throwing the play stick.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aboriginal-australian-ceremony] The winner throws the weet weet furthest or the most accurately.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The **Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies** (**AIATSIS**), established as the **Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies** (**AIAS**) in 1964, is an independent Australian Government statutory authority.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] It is a collecting, publishing, and research institute and is considered to be Australia's premier resource for information about the cultures and societies of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The institute is a leader in ethical research and the handling of culturally sensitive material.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The collection at AIATSIS has been built through over 50 years of research and engagement with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities and is now a source of language and culture revitalisation, native title research, and Indigenous family and community history.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is located on Acton Peninsula in Canberra, Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In the late 1950s, there was an increasing focus on the global need for anthropological research into 'disappearing cultures'.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This trend was also emerging in Australia in the work of researchers of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, leading to a proposal by W.C.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Wentworth MP for the conception of an Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies (AIAS) in 1959.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The proposal was made as a submission to Cabinet, and argued for a more comprehensive approach by the Australian Government to the recording of Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples and cultures.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 1960, a Cabinet sub-committee assessed the proposal and formed a working party at the Australian National University (ANU) to consider the viability of the proposal.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] One of their first actions was to appoint W.E.H.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Stanner to organise a conference on the state of Aboriginal Studies in Australia, to be held in 1961 at the ANU.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Academics and anthropologists in the field of Aboriginal Studies attended the conference, and contributed research papers published in a conference report in 1963.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] No Aboriginal people were present at the conference.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Prime Minister at the time, Robert Menzies, appointed an Interim Council in 1961.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The role of the Interim Council was to plan for a national Aboriginal research organisation and establish how this organisation would interact with existing research and scientific bodies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Interim Council was also tasked with immediately developing a programme that would identify and address urgent research needs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Interim Council consisted of 16 members and was chaired by Deputy Vice-Chancellor of the ANU, Professor A.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Trendall, officially recognised as the first chair of the institute now known as AIATSIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In August 1962, a draft constitution for the institute was submitted to the Menzies government, and rejected.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Interim Council completed a revised constitution in July 1963.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Amendments to the document included the change from the title 'director' to 'principal' of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This version of the constitution would go on to form the basis for the creation of the new Australian Institute for Aboriginal Studies the following year.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies was established as a statutory authority under an Act of Parliament in June 1964.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The mission of the Institute at that time has been described as "to record language, song, art, material culture, ceremonial life and social structure before those traditions perished in the face of European ways".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This notion is also reflected in the Institute's official functions, as recorded in the Reading of the Bill in Parliament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] 2. to treat as a matter of urgency those studies for which the source materials are disappearing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] 3. to establish and conduct a documentation centre on the Aborigines, and a library of books, manuscripts and other relevant material, both for the use of scholars and for public education.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] 4. to encourage co-operation with and between scholars in universities, museums, and other institutions engaged in studies of the Aborigines, and with appropriate private bodies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] 5. to publish and to support the publication of the results of research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] 6. to co-operate with appropriate bodies concerning the financing of research, the preservation of sites, and the collection of records.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] 7. to promote as and when necessary the training of research workers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] 8. to establish and maintain relations with relevant international bodies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIAS had a twenty-two member Council, composed mainly of academics, and had a foundation membership of one hundred.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The founding Principal of the newly formed institute was Frederick McCarthy, a professional anthropologist and graduate of Sydney University who had spent nearly 30 years working in the field.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The creation of the AIAS provided an opportunity for greater cross-discipline interaction in fields relating to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander studies in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Institute's founding principal, Fred McCarthy, was an advocate of film as an important part of research methodology as early as his tenure as curator of anthropology at the Australian Museum in Sydney in the 1940s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This was evident in the contributions he made during his involvement in establishing the AIAS and also as its principal, in continuing to support the development of the AIAS Film Unit and championing ethnographic film in global forums.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In the early years of the AIAS, the Film Unit largely outsourced early filmmaking work to other companies, or worked in collaboration with the Commonwealth Film Unit (as early as 1962).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] But over the next 30 years, the Film Unit would go on to produce "one of the largest assembly of ethnographic films created in the world".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In keeping with the AIAS official function "to publish and to support the publication of the results of research", a publishing arm of the institute was established in 1964.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Publishing under the name Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies, the publishing arm released a range of papers and research findings, including in the fields of linguistics, demography, physical anthropology, history and musicology.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The early work of the AIAS is credited with increasing interaction between academics in different fields, as well as establishing the foundations for the extensive collections AIATSIS holds today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] But before 1970, there had never been an Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander member on the AIAS Council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The 1970s marked a period of change for the AIAS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This began with the appointment of the first Aboriginal member of the AIAS Council in 1970.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Phillip Roberts, an Alawa man, served on the council from September 1970 until June 1972.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This was followed in 1971 with a second Aboriginal Council member, Senator Neville Bonner, who served on Council until 1974 and for a second term in the late 1970s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] And again in 1972, with the appointment of Dick Roughsey to replace Phillip Roberts at the end of his term.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The appointment of Phillip Roberts to the Council reflected a growing pressure for an increase in Aboriginal representation within the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] But the move did not allay the belief held by some Aboriginal activists that the AIAS was engaging in 'tokenism' in the extent to which Aboriginal people were involved in the administration of Aboriginal Studies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The changes to the Institute that would take place in the following decade were also influenced by the shifting social and political landscape in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal rights movement was growing and Aboriginal people were demanding a voice on Council, consultation with communities and an increased focus on projects relevant to the needs of Indigenous people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 1972, the Whitlam government was elected.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Their policy of self-determination for Aboriginal people echoed calls for greater Aboriginal involvement in the administration and functions of the AIAS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The new government was also responsible for a significant boost to AIAS funding.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The appointment of Peter Ucko in 1972 as Principal of the AIAS has since been described as the beginning of an increase in involvement of Aboriginal people in the workings of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In his time as Principal, Ucko was responsible for implementing a policy later labelled "Aboriginalisation", which was aimed at opening up the institute to Aboriginal involvement and representation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This policy was influenced by a document circulated in 1974, called the Eaglehawk and Crow letter, which criticised the current model of academic research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The policy and structural changes to the Institute continued throughout the 1970s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal Advisory Committee was established in 1975, and consisted of the six Aboriginal members of the AIAS Council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Early recommendations including increased representation of Aboriginal people on committees and the AIAS Council as well as employment at the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The committee was renamed in 1978, to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Advisory Committee.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 1975–1976, a category of research grants for Aboriginal researchers was introduced.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The emergence of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people filling the role of 'cultural practitioner', travelling to the AIAS to provide advice on projects and research being undertaken, was also documented from around 1976 onwards.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The time Peter Ucko spent as Principal of the AIAS saw a phase of "rapid expansion" for the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The AIAS Film Unit that had operated in Sydney until 1973 was re-established in Canberra in 1975.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Prominent American-born ethnographic filmmaker David MacDougall was appointed the Director of this new AIAS Film Unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] With his wife and filmmaking partner Judith MacDougall and Kim McKenzie, the Film Unit operated until 1988 when its functions were absorbed back into the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] During the MacDougall/McKenzie era, a new style of ethnographic film was explored.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] One that moved away from film as a scientific record in favour of telling the story of individuals lives.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The filmmakers also practised a more collaborative approach to their films, and chose to use translations and subtitles to give direct access to the subjects voice and thoughts rather than the dominant 'voice of god' narration style.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] One of the most notable films produced towards the end of this period was *Waiting for Harry*, a prize-winning film directed by Kim McKenzie with anthropologist Les Hiatt and now considered to exemplify the "style of collaborative filmmaking" the Film Unit favoured in their work.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The power of film to "influence opinion" was becoming increasingly recognised and with this, the lack of representation of Aboriginal people telling their own stories.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 1978, a meeting chaired by prominent activist and academic Marcia Langton expressed these concerns, arguing for greater access to film and video in Aboriginal communities, and training in film production by the AIAS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] By the following year, the AIAS Film Unit had begun to implement a training program and had started employing trainee Aboriginal filmmakers on productions by the early 1980s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The AIAS began presenting a biennial Wentworth Lecture in 1978, named as a tribute to W.C.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Wentworth for his role in establishing the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The lecture is presented by prominent person with knowledge or experience relating to issues affecting Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples in Australia today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The expansion of the Institute continued into the 1980s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal Studies Press began publishing the Australian Aboriginal Studies Journal in 1983, a peer-reviewed journal aimed at "promoting high-quality research in Australian Indigenous studies".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 1982, the AIAS established a task force that identified the prevailing need for further 'Aboriginalisation' of the Institute's workforce.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] At the time, there were four Aboriginal staff members, making up around 7% of the total staff.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This was followed in 1985 with the creation of the role of Aboriginal Studies Coordination Officer within the AIAS, whose responsibilities involved improving access for Aboriginal people to the research and resources of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The *After 200 Years* project was launched in 1985, aiming to fill some of the gaps in the AIAS photographic collection; particularly images of daily life in the southern, urban parts of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Aboriginal involvement in selecting subject matter, photographing and documenting the collection was a major part of the project.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The three-year project culminated in the publication of a book containing hundreds of photographs of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, and selected by them to represent their community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Rock Art Protection Program (RAPP) commenced in 1986 following a request for such an initiative by the then Minister of Aboriginal Affairs Clyde Holding.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The aim of the RAPP was to protect Australian Indigenous rock art.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Grants were approved by the institute to fund various projects related to rock art protection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The collections were also expanding, and by 1987 the AIATSIS library encompassed the print collections, a special Bibliographic Section and the Resource Centre (which contained the Institute's audiovisual materials).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Between 1987 and 1989, the survival of the AIAS as an independent statutory body was tied to a proposal for a new statutory commission that would take over all aspects of the Aboriginal Affairs portfolio.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This commission would become the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC), conceived in an Act of Parliament in 1989.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The AIAS would not be folded into this commission; instead it would be recreated under a new Act with a new name.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The *Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies (AIATSIS) Act* was passed by parliament in 1989, replacing the AIAS Act.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The newly established AIATSIS had a reduced Council consisting of nine members, with the AIATSIS Act specifying that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people hold a minimum of five of these Council positions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The new Act also established a Research Advisory Committee, to assess research applications and advise the council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal Studies Press published their best-selling Aboriginal Australia map in 1996, based on research conducted for the Encyclopaedia of Aboriginal Australia, edited by David Horton.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 2001, the Institute launched a two-year Library Digitisation Pilot Program (LDPP).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Among the items digitised, catalogued and made available online were 267 volumes of the *Dawn* and *New Dawn* magazines held in the AIATSIS collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS also distributed over 2000 free copies of these magazines on CD-Rom, to Indigenous organisations, schools and libraries in New South Wales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Throughout this period, AIATSIS continued to undertake projects focused on the digitisation of collection materials, including their holdings of the complete back catalogue of *Koori Mail*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This involved scanning over 35,000 pages from 500 editions of the newspaper, with searchable copies launched on the AIATSIS website in partnership with Koori Mail in 2011.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] As part of their research functions, AIATSIS also initiated a number of public programs and research related events during this time that are still run today.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The institute has convened the National Indigenous Studies Conference every two years since 2001 and the National Native Title Conference every year since 2002.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The *After 200 Years* photographic project was revisited in 2014 with an exhibition of images at Parliament House, Canberra, to coincide with AIATSIS' 50-year anniversary.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 2020, following consultation with the United Ngunnawal Elders Council and the Winanggaay Ngunnawal Language Group, the AIATSIS building in Acton was officially named *Maraga*, which means a strong shield.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] On 2 February 2024, coinciding with its 60th anniversary, AIATSIS opened a new facility in Mparntwe-Alice Springs, building on its long partnership with First Nations Media Australia, which is based in the city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS staff, six of whom are Indigenous locals (of seven in total; intended to grow to up to 24) located at the new centre will work closely with local people to take care of the cultural heritage from the region.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] There is a dedicated ancestry section in the new centre, which before its completion was referred to as AIATSIS Alice Springs Engagement and Digitisation Centre and is now officially known as AIATSIS Central Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The centre will be run in collaboration with the Northern Territory Government, and allow access to AIATSIS materials for people living in Central Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] An exhibition titled *To Know, To Respect, To Care* is on at the centre until 14 June 2024.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The official opening was attended by Linda Burney, the Minister for Indigenous Australians, and NT Minister for Arts, Culture and Heritage Chansey Paech.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is an Australian Government statutory authority established under the *Public Governance, Performance and Accountability Act 2013*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] As of 2024 it is under the portfolio of the Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet, and Hon Linda Burney, Minister for Indigenous Australians, is the responsible minister.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] 6. to encourage understanding, in the general community, of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander societies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The AIATSIS Council is a governing body designed to oversee and steer the functions and direction of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The role and responsibilities of the council are mandated in the *AIATSIS Act 1989*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Council consists of nine members; four are elected by the institute's membership and five appointed by the Minister.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] According to the AIATSIS Act 1989, one person appointed by the Minister must be a Torres Strait Islander and the four other people appointed by the Minister must be Aboriginal persons or Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The four Council members elected by the Institute's membership must be members themselves.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Various advisory committees exist to assist the Council as well as the chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Indigenous Caucus is a working group providing a forum for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander staff to meet and discuss workplace issues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Indigenous Caucus was revitalised in 2003–2004 and contributed to the development of policies and procedures in that year, notably AIATSIS' Indigenous Training and Career Development Plan.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 2013, the Indigenous Caucus developed a formal Service Charter and elected an Executive consisting of three members.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Native Title Research Advisory Committee (NTRAC) provides advice to the CEO on the research program of the Native Title Research Unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Research Advisory Committee (RAC) is responsible for assessing and advising on AIATSIS research projects and programs, including research grants.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] RAC functions are established in the AIATSIS Act.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Research Ethics Committee (REC) is responsible for advising AIATSIS on the ethics of the research proposals by staff or grantees of AIATSIS, as well as research carried out through the Institute's external collaborations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The roles in the Research Ethics Committee are based on the National Statement published by the National Health and Medical Research Council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The AIATSIS Act sets the organisation the task of conducting, facilitating and promoting research in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies and training Indigenous researchers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] For over 50 years, AIATSIS has conducted research across a range of areas of study relevant to Indigenous peoples, culture, heritage, knowledge and experiences.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This has led to a diverse research history; from languages and archaeological research, land rights, and political engagement, to contemporary topics in health and commerce.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The AIATSIS collections not only contain priceless records of Australia's Indigenous cultural heritage, but provide a significant national and international research infrastructure for research by, for and about Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is one of Australia's Publicly Funded Research Agencies (PFRA), alongside organisations such as CSIRO and the Australian Institute of Marine Science.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is Australia's only non-science PFRA.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Currently AIATSIS undertakes research in six priority areas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The institute is a leader in ethical research and the handling of culturally sensitive material. and holds in its collections many unique and irreplaceable items of cultural, historical and spiritual significance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS published the *Guidelines for Ethical Research in Australian Indigenous Studies* (referred to as GERAIS) in 1999.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This was a document considered to be the leading ethics guidelines for conducting research in and with Indigenous communities in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] GERAIS was regularly revised and significantly updated in 2012.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] GERAIS was replaced in 2020 by *AIATSIS Code of Ethics for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Research (the AIATSIS Code)*, which supersedes GERAIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Accompanying it is "A Guide to applying The AIATSIS Code of Ethics for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Research".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 2013, AIATSIS was involved in the review of two National Health and Medical Research Council research ethics guidelines relating to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS began undertaking native title research activities through the Native Title Research Unit in 1993, following the 1992 *Mabo v Queensland* High Court decision.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Native Title Research Advisory Committee, the Research Advisory Committee, and the AIATSIS Council oversee the work conducted in Native Title and traditional ownership research at AIATSIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS conducts a range of research projects relating to Native Title and traditional ownership, including Native Title and cultural heritage, Native Title and fresh and sea water, and Prescribed Body Corporates.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The role of Native Title research at AIATSIS is to monitor outcomes of Native Title and through research and study, provide advice on Native Title policy development.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Institute publishes a range of materials relating to Native Title including books, discussion papers, research reports and a Native Title Newsletter.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS also provides a Native Title Research and Access Officer, who is responsible for assisting Native Title claimants to access materials from the AIATSIS collections in support of their claim.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Up until 2019, AIATSIS also contributed to Native Title policy and research by co-organising the Annual National Native Title Conference.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] However, in 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic in Australia, the conference was cancelled, and in 2021 it merged with the National Indigenous Research Conference, creating a five-day event known as the AIATSIS Summit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS publishes a number of resources for anyone wishing to undertake research into their own family history.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The *Family History kit* is aimed at providing the basics for tracing Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander heritage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] It contains guides to AIATSIS' own resources, including the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Biographical Index (ABI) and digitised collection materials, as well as guides to external resources that may help with family history research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] General guidance is also provided regarding research resources specific to Indigenous family history research, historical name conventions and usage and confirmation of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander heritage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS also provides research support to Link-Up case workers and researchers around Australia, who are assisting members of the Stolen Generations to reconnect with their family and heritage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In keeping with its mandated functions, AIATSIS publishes the results of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies through their publishing arm, Aboriginal Studies Press (ASP).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Institute began publishing in 1962 with *A demographic survey of the Aboriginal population of the Northern Territory, with special reference to Bathurst Island Mission*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] This and other early publications were released under the imprint Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies, the former title of AIATSIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The ASP publishing imprint was trademarked in 2002, but was operating as the publishing arm of AIATSIS as early as the publication of Helen Ross' *Just For Living* in 1987.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The **AIATSIS Research Publications** became an imprint in 2011 and its stated purpose is to publish scholarly research that is derived from the AIATSIS Research Program.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] All Aboriginal Studies Press-branded titles are peer-reviewed and the majority are published concurrently in print and several ebook formats.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The first phone app was published in 2013, and was shortlisted for the 2013 Mobile Awards.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Titles published by ASP have included research reports, monographs, biographies, autobiographies, family and community histories, and children's books.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Since 2005 the list has aligned more closely with the Institute's research focus.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Most publications derive from academic research, some funded by AIATSIS.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] ASP publishes books by both Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander and non-Indigenous authors who are writing in the field of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In some cases Aboriginal authors, like Doreen Kartinyeri and Joan Martin, have chosen to write in collaboration with non-Aboriginal oral historians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Publishing Advisory Committee makes recommendations to the AIATSIS Principal and Aboriginal Studies Press about which manuscripts to publish from those submitted.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] It has relationships with distributors and resellers for both national and international print and ebook distribution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Another widely used resource published by Aboriginal Studies Press is the **Aboriginal Australia map**, created by David Horton.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The Aboriginal Australia map represents the general locations of larger groupings of Aboriginal people, using research that was conducted during the development of *The Encyclopaedia of Aboriginal Australia*, which was another significant ASP publication.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Previous milestone publications included the book *After 200 Years*, a collaboration showcasing photographs and stories of Aboriginal people as selected by members of those communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Both books are now out of print and only available in libraries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] ASP also publishes the Stanner Award winner for a scholarly manuscript (not fiction or poetry) by an Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander, which recognises the importance of being published to emerging academics.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The prize includes mentoring and editorial support by ASP, as well as publication of the manuscript, A$5,000, and a glass sculpture by Jenni Kemarre Martiniello.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The biennial award is named in honour of the anthropologist W.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] (Bill) Stanner, who played an important role in establishing the AIAS, and the ongoing development of the institute.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] In 1996, *Auntie Rita*, a biography of Rita Huggins co-written by her and her daughter Jackie Huggins, won the award.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] Anna Haebich won the 1999 award for her work *Broken circles: Fragmenting indigenous families 1800–2000*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The 2011 award was won by human rights advocate and lawyer Hannah McGlade in 2011.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The AIATSIS website hosts the **AUSTLANG** database, an informative source of information on all known Aboriginal Australian languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] With its beginnings on a card file compiled in the 1990s, the Indigenous Languages Database (ILDB) was developed based on the Language Thesaurus maintained by the AIATSIS library since the 1960s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The online version of AUSTLANG was developed in 2005, revised and released to the public in 2008, and after more redevelopment work, a refined version was released in 2018.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS hosts a range of special events and research workshops, symposiums and conferences.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] AIATSIS is located on the Acton Peninsula in a building that was newly built for the Institute and opened in 2001.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The building was officially opened by the Honourable W.C.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] As part of the opening the Ngunnawal people, the traditional owners of the land on which the AIATSIS building stands performed a Welcome to Country and smoking ceremony, and the Anbarra people from North Central Arnhem Land performed a friendship ceremony, known as the Rom ceremony.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The architect, Howard Ragatt of the firm Ashton Raggatt McDougall designed the building for AIATSIS and for its neighbour on the Acton Peninsula, the National Museum of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] During design of the AIATSIS building, it was reoriented from original plans to save two apple box trees that were identified as significant to the Peninsula.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The building cost $13.75 million and was funded by the Commonwealth Government's Centenary of Federation Grants Program.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The design of the AIATSIS building has been the subject of differing interpretations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The rear of the building has been described as a black copy of pioneer architect Le Corbusier's 1920s Villa Savoye in France.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The architect, Howard Raggatt, was quoted as confirming this influence but has also stated that it is designed to be reminiscent of Sidney Nolan's famous paintings of Ned Kelly.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] A new building is planned in Canberra, to be located in a precinct to be named Ngurra, on the shores of Lake Burley Griffin, in the Parliamentary Triangle.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The new precinct A$316.5 million will also include a new centre for learning and knowledge, and a resting place for ancestral remains of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from around the nation who are unable to be located in their Country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The name *Ngurra* occurs in several Aboriginal languages, meaning "home", "camp", "a place of belonging or inclusion".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] A design competition was held in 2022 to select the architects for the project.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] A new AIATSIS facility known as AIATSIS Central Australia was opened on 2 February 2024 in Alice Springs/Mparntwe, to serve Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people in Central Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p01] The offices and exhibition spaces were created from two vacant retail premises in Todd Mall.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS is considered to be Australia's premier resource for information about the cultures and societies of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS is the only Commonwealth of Australia institution responsible for collecting and maintaining materials documenting the oral and visual traditions and histories of Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The Institute identifies its collection as a "keeping place for culturally significant objects" that is "a resource for anybody looking to improve their knowledge of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander history and culture".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The institute's holdings represent thousands of years of history and more than 500 Australian Indigenous languages, dialects and groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] This collection supports, and is a result of, research in the fields of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] An independent assessment in 2014 confirmed that AIATSIS holds over 6 million feet of film, over 40,000 hours of audio, 12,800 unpublished manuscripts and record series, 653,000 photographs, and 120,000 print and published materials (3,000 of which are rare books) among other miscellanea.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] As of 2024 it was estimated that it holds over a million cultural items, which include 42,000 hours of audio, over 700,000 photographs, and around 6 million feet of film.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The Audiovisual Archives also holds copies of the first audio recorded in Australia; a series of ethnographic wax cylinder recordings made in the Torres Strait Islands in 1898.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The Cambridge Anthropological Expedition to the Torres Strait, led by Alfred Cort Haddon, recorded songs and speech from Mer/Murray Island, Mabuiag/Jervis Island, Saibai Island, Tudu Island and Iama/Yam Island.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Since the establishment of the Institute in 1964, the AIATSIS collection has been developed through acquisition by donation, gift and purchase or, through materials created and collected during the work of ethnographic field researchers and filmmakers funded by the AIATSIS grants program.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The collection has also been built through deposits of materials, an arrangement which permits the original owners to assign access and use conditions appropriate to the cultural information contained in the items.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Once material has been acquired by AIATSIS, the Institute faces the challenges of maintaining a cultural resource collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] This is achieved through a collection management plan that involves processes of recording and cataloguing, and appropriate storage and handling to extend the life of physical items and preserving their content through format shifting.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Storage of collection items in climate-controlled vaults, to maintain their integrity and to minimise contact with deteriorating agents such as moisture and light.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The Institute also follows international archiving guidelines for the storage and preservation of materials.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] There are a wide variety of analogue photograph, tape and film formats held in the AIATSIS collection, which pose special preservation and future access risks.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The age of some of these formats and materials, combined with the varying conditions in which they were stored prior to their acquisition by AIATSIS, heightens the deterioration of the media.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Another preservation issue inherent in these analogue materials is the machines that can play back that particular format, as in some cases the material and the playback device are no longer manufactured.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] To manage these risks and maintain future access to the collection, preservation of the actual content contained in collection items is also achieved through a program of digitisation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Due to the potential issues of long-term archiving and storage of digital items, the opposite process is often employed to ensure access and preservation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] In the case of digital publications and manuscripts, the originals will often be printed and incorporated into the print collections as an additional preservation measure.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The AIATSIS collection holds material that is sensitive and/or secret/sacred to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] In accordance with its founding Act, and as part of their collection management plan, AIATSIS adheres to strict protocols when handling and processing these sensitive items.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The institute also supports and adheres to the protocols developed by the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Library, Information and Resource Network (ATSILIRN).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Restricted visual media such as photographs and printed items are stored separately to the rest of the collection and audio and moving image items are not played until any cultural requirements are checked.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Restricted material must also be carefully handled during digitisation, which means that the work is carried out in secured conditions such as enclosed booths and by staff that can meet the protocols of the item being digitised.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS launched its Library Digitisation Pilot Program in 2001, before which the Library had no dedicated digitisation equipment or policies for managing digital materials.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] This two-year program was originally funded by the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC), and involved the creation of digital collections across the institution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Since then AIATSIS has continued to incorporate digitisation of the collection into its management plan, but have publicly stated that an increase in funding is required for the institute to digitise some of the at risk formats held in the collection before those items are lost.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Given these limitations, AIATSIS prioritises the selection of materials for digitisation using factors including significance of the item/s, the level of deterioration, cultural protocols, copyright status, and client demand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] One of the identified priorities of the program is to digitise and preserve all of the audiovisual collection currently on endangered magnetic tape formats by the 2025 deadline set by UNESCO.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The collection is housed in the AIATSIS building on Acton Peninsula and is accessible through a number of resources.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The AIATSIS Library is open to the public and holds a range of printed materials including manuscripts, journals, readers in different Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander languages, dictionaries, published books and rare books, maps, and posters.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Access to AIATSIS' print and manuscript collections can be made through the Library's Stanner Reading Room and the film, sound and pictorial collections by appointment through the Access Unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] These physical access points are open limited hours.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The AIATSIS Digitisation Program contributes to increased access to the collection; whether access is through on site resources, the provision of copies of materials or the sharing of the collection online.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Due to increasing obsolescence of analogue formats, AIATSIS identifies digitisation as the way to preserve those items for future generations to access.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] This is considered to be particularly important for facilitating "remote access by Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities" as well as for access by researchers and the general public.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The AIATSIS Access Unit runs a program called Return of Material to Indigenous Communities (ROMTIC), through which Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander clients are provided with up to twenty copies of collection materials that relate to their language group or family.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] This service is limited to items that have been preserved, so AIATSIS' digitisation program has allowed an increasing number of digital items available to ROMTIC clients.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS also makes the collection available through a series of online exhibitions and digitised collection material published on their website.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Access to the AIATSIS collection is also dictated by legislation governing the Institute and in some instances by legal agreements outlining the terms under which collection materials can be used.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The terms for access to the AIATSIS collection are in the first instance set by the AIATSIS Act, Section 41.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The conditions referred to in Section 41(1) of the AIATSIS Act are usually covered in the agreement that AIATSIS enters into when material is deposited.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] These agreements, along with the section 41(2) of the Act, can govern the way that unpublished material can be accessed and used.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Access to and use of material in the AIATSIS collection is also subject to the terms set out in the Copyright Act (1968).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] When a donation or deposit is being made, AIATSIS requests to be made aware of any sensitive items included in the material.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The secret or sacred nature of information contained in many collection items is an important factor in access to the AIATSIS collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] In response to these complex issues AIATSIS developed an overarching Access and Use Policy in 2014, to "manage legal and cultural rights over material while maximising accessibility".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] Since its inception, AIATSIS has developed and maintained a range of resources to enhance discoverability of the collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] One of the most significant of these resources is the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Biographical Index (ABI).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The ABI had its beginnings in 1979 as a non-selective biographical register of names, constructed using information on Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from published material in the collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] In the early years of the biographical register, it was hoped it could "provide an important record of the achievements of Aboriginal people, and be a source of pride for generations to come".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] The former Perfect Pictures Database appears to have been superseded by the Photographic Collection, which contains around 400,000 (and growing) digitised images, and more than 700,000 images in total.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] For copyright and cultural reasons, the images may only be viewed in the Stanner Reading Room, but caption information is available online, and copies of the images may be requested.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/aiatsis-p02] AIATSIS also hosts or contributes to other online resources, aimed at facilitating access to and understanding of the collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Governance of the area is determined by the *Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara Land Rights Act 1981* (or APYLRA), whereby an elected executive board reports to the Premier of South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The APY's administration centre is located at Umuwa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] A large portion of the APY Lands was formerly the **North-West Aboriginal Reserve**.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Due to its links with the Northern Territory and proximity to the border, the APY Lands do not observe daylight savings unlike the rest of South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The time zone observed throughout the year is Australian Central Standard Time (UTC+9:30), in line with Darwin rather than Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The Pitjantjatjara and Yankunytjatjara people (*aṉangu*) had lived in this area for many thousands of years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Even after the British began to colonise the Australian continent from 1788 onwards, and the colonisation of South Australia from 1836, the *aṉangu* remained more or less undisturbed for many more years, apart from very occasional encounters with a variety of European explorers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In 1921, with white settlement now beginning to encroach on the *aṉangu*'s traditional land, the South Australian Government proclaimed the North-West Aboriginal Reserve.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] This Reserve consisted of most of what is now known as the APY Lands, with the exception of the eastern part of the APY Lands, which was given over to pastoral leases to Europeans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In 1937, the Presbyterian Church council, spearheaded by Charles Duguid, established the Ernabella Mission on the Lands at the place now known as Pukatja.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] By the 1950s, many *aṉangu* were living at the Ernabella Mission, while many others lived at camps on pastoral leases on what are now the Lands, or nearby, where they would work.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Those pastoral leases included Granite Downs, Everard Park, Victory Downs, De Rose Hill, Kenmore Park, and Mount Cavanagh.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In 1961, to prevent overcrowding at Ernabella Mission, the Church established what became the community of Amata, but which was originally known as Musgrave Park.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] At the same time the Church also established what is now the community of Kaltjiti, but which was then known as Fregon.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In 1968, what is now the community of Indulkana was established by the South Australian Government, as a base from which to provide welfare services to *aṉangu* living in camps on pastoral leases, where work was becoming increasingly difficult to find.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] At that time, the surrounding area was excised from pastoral leases and declared the Indulkana Aboriginal Reserve.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The body now known as Aṉangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara was formed in 1981 by the passing of the *Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara Land Rights Act 1981* by the Parliament of South Australia under Premier Don Dunstan, and includes the Pitjantjatjara, Yankunytjatjara and Ngaanyatjarra groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] "Ara Irititja" is a project of the APY, commenced in 1994 to identify, copy and electronically record historical materials about the Anangu (Pitjantjatjara/Yankunytjatjara people).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Its purpose is to prevent the loss of the history, and to allow the teaching of it to others in the community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] By 2007 the peoples of the region had not had any major economic development, apart from tourism, but there had been proposals to mine in the area.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The opal fields of Mintabie came under separate governance that time.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The Musgrave Block in the Lands has been viewed as having billions of dollars in potential mineral deposits and petroleum.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] But *anangu* have been wary of opening up the area to mining, concerned about the impact on sacred sites and the environment.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In 2003 mining companies were conducting discussions to try to allay these worries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] A 2004 parliamentary report on an inquiry by a select committee led by Minister for Aboriginal Affairs Terry Roberts examined the shortcomings of the 1981 Act, which had not addressed entrenched social and economic problems in the Lands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The review noted shortcomings in the delivery of human services and infrastructure, and identified a "need to address the issue of the overall governance of the AP Lands and to formalise arrangements within an Act of Parliament and/or the Constitution of Anangu Pitjantjatjara".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] After wide consultation and consideration of many submissions, the committee made 15 recommendations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] One of these was the establishment of a permanent police presence, as one of several strategies used to combat the problems of petrol sniffing and family violence.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Also in July, Commonwealth Indigenous Affairs Minister Mal Brough offered federal help for a "drug and alcohol crackdown" in South Australian Aboriginal lands – such as the APY Lands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In early August 2007, the Rann South Australian Labor Government announced A$ 34 million package to "improve well-being of Aboriginal people" in the APY Lands. $25m was to be spent on improving housing and most of the remaining $8m on law enforcement in Amata and Pukatja.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In November, SA Police Commissioner Mal Hyde announced the signing of a new enterprise agreement for South Australia Police that would include incentive packages to lure police to work in rural and remote areas such as the Lands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] This amendment changed the licensing system for residential and commercial premises effective 1 July 2012, allowing the Minister responsible for the *Opal Mining Act* to grant licences.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] A 2017 report found many instances of non-compliance with the 2009 Amendment as well as other problems occurring in the settlement of Mintabie.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] It recommended closure of the township, with control reverting to APY.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] After an appeal by residents failed, the final eviction date for the township was set at 31 December 2019.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In March 2024, the Kulilaya Festival was held at Umuwa to celebrate the 40th anniversary of the 1981 *APY Land Rights Act*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] It had been delayed for three years owing to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Artists, musicians, and dancers presented their history and stories to commemorate the occasion.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The word *kulilaya* approximates to the meaning of "listen", and was the name of a land rights protest song that was sung frequently in the late 1970s and early 1980s, and since then sung regularly by the Ernabella Choir, the APY Choir, and the Iwiri Choir.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Several inma ceremonies were performed, politicians from across the spectrum attended the festival, and performers included Dem Mob, Docker River Band, the Iwiri Choir, Mala, the Pukatja Band, and Desert Rain.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In the summer of 2025/6, APY has been plagued by feral camels in search of water.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The animals have damaged infrastructure and many have died, creating a problem with disposal of carcasses.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The Musgrave Ranges, straddling the border between South Australia and the Northern Territory and the Mann Ranges and Tomkinson Ranges, both in the north-west of South Australia, stretch from east to west on the southern side of the NT border.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The APY area includes isolated ranges and hills and large sandhill plains, and APY people also have affiliations with land in the NT to the Petermann Ranges, and in Western Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] There is a large palaeovalley, a geological term for an ancient, buried river, underneath the APY Lands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] A map of the geological formation, complete with scientific and technical terminology, has been translated into Pitjantjatjara by a team of translators, based on the English-language map developed by government agencies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] There is a long strip of limestone breaking through red soil near Fregon/Kaltjiti, where a new water source was found in 2019.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The area is one of two places in the world which have landlocked tectonic plates, and drilling samples have been estimated to be between 5 and 10 million years old.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] To the north of the APY Lands, the MacDonnell Shire Council was created by the Northern Territory in 2008, renamed MacDonnell Region in 2014, spanning the south of the Territory from west to east.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The South Australian LGA to the south of APY Lands is Maralinga Tjarutja (with the District Council of Coober Pedy to the east of that, but not adjoining APY).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The APY LGA encompasses a number of settlements of a range of sizes, many of them being located in the Musgrave Ranges.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] An interactive map shows the location of communities and further information about each on the Paper Tracker website.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The main communities include Indulkana (Iwantja), Mimili, Kaltjiti (Fregon), Pukatja (Ernabella), Amata, Pipalyatjara, and Watarru; the larger homelands are Kalka, Kanpi, Nyapari and Yunyarinyi (homeland).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The APY administration centre of the Lands is located at Umuwa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Mintabie was an opal-mining town, leased back to the Government of South Australia between 1981 and 2019, when the residents were evicted.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Governance of the area is determined by the *APY Land Rights Act 1981* (amended 2017), whereby an elected executive board reports to the Premier of South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The board appoints a general manager for a fixed term.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Richard King was elected by the board in April 2015, and his term was extended for a year in March 2023, despite opposition by some councillors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In August 2025, the South Australian Government announced the appointment of administrators to run the lands for three months from 3 September, after a review found the reappointment of its general manager was constitutionally invalid under the *APY Land Rights Act*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] King said that, after 12 years in the job, he would return to his family in Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The area is usually referred to as the APY Lands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] A permit is required for visitors to any community on the APY Lands, as they are freehold lands owned by the Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The *Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara Lands Rights (Miscellaneous) Amendment Act 2016* determined the boundaries of seven APY electorates to elect the executive board of Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The 2006 ABS census figures were not vastly different.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The total number of residents was slightly lower, at 2,230, but with a higher percentage born in Australia, at 98%.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] There were fewer speakers of Pitjantjatjara (58.6%), and more Yankuntjatjara (14.3%).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] More (46.1%) identified as being affiliated with the Uniting Church, and a similar percentage rented their homes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The upgrade to the Main Access Road is a major project, originally scheduled to begin in 2015 and be completed in 2019, at a cost of A$106.25m (split 80/20 between federal and state governments).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] It is an upgrade to 210 kilometres (130 mi) of the main access road between the Stuart Highway and Pukatja/Ernabella, and 21 kilometres (13 mi) of community and airstrip access roads in Pukatja, Umuwa, Kaltjiti/Fregon, Mimili and Iwantja/Indulkana.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] It is expected to deliver safer road travel, better access to employment opportunities, improved delivery of food supplies, improved living standards, etc.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In January 2019 it was reported that construction started in 2017, and should be completed by 2021.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Based in Umuwa, Anangu Pitjantjatjara Services (AP Services), an incorporated body established in 1993, provides essential services such as roads and housing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Regional Anangu Services Aboriginal Corporation (RASAC) was established in early 2010 as an offshoot of AP Services, and is now the biggest employer of APY people, with headquarters in Alice Springs and seven community depots.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] It delivers services such as rental accommodation, aerodromes, building repairs and maintenance, civil works, community patrols, fuel supplies, homeland services and municipal services.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] A few months after his election in early 2018, Premier Steven Marshall, also responsible for Aboriginal Affairs, visited the APY Lands as part of his "whole-of-government" plan which aims to measure SA's progress on improving services to Aboriginal communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] He reported afterwards that employment, especially for young people, was a major issue that needed addressing; and the other one was housing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] His government was working on a new funding agreement for remote housing with the federal government, after the 10-year National Partnership Agreement on Remote Housing had ended on 30 June.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Susan Tilley, Uniting Communities Aboriginal policy and advocacy manager, said that there were about 75 families still on the waiting list for housing, and that maintenance of existing stock and new housing had to be continued.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In 2014, a Mobile Dialysis Unit, a specially designed truck fitted with three dialysis chairs started operation, visiting remote Aboriginal communities across South Australia, including Pukatja, Mimili, Kaltjiti and Amata in the APY Lands, as well as Marla, Yalata, Coober Pedy, and Leigh Creek.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] It is run from Purple House, a renal health clinic in Alice Springs, over 400 kilometres (250 mi) away.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In July 2018, Health Minister Greg Hunt and Ken Wyatt, then Minister for Indigenous Health, announced increased funding for a number of health initiatives, including expanding renal health units in remote parts, through the National Health and Medical Research Council (NHMRC).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In November 2019, a four-bed dialysis clinic was opened in Pukatja, named after Kinyin Mckenzie, who died in Alice Springs while receiving dialysis.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The first such clinic in remote South Australia, it was funded mostly by the federal government, but boosted by the sale of paintings by Ernabella Arts, which raised A$170,000 towards the centre.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] At full capacity, the clinic can provide dialysis for up to 16 patients, but there is still a need for some short-stay housing to accommodate those who travel from elsewhere for treatment at Pukatja.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] As of 2018, the APY Lands were served by police stations situated at Amata, Ernabella, Mimili, Murputja, Umuwa and the town of Marla.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Specialist policing support is located at Umuwa, including CIB and domestic violence investigators.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The station at Umuwa has not been permanently staffed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] As of 2020 a new, permanent policing complex is being built at Umawa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] It will accommodate officers with specialist response capabilities, as well provide a base for a mobile unit which will be deployed in Fregon/Kaljiti, Indulkana and Pipalytjara.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The service will work closely with child protection service agencies address child abuse and family violence issues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The 2019–2020 Government of South Australia agency budget estimates the completion date as June 2021, with a total spend of A$4.28 million.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] SA Water operates desalination plants at Indulkana, Mimili, Kaltjiti (Fregon) and Yunyarinyi (Kenmore Park), which treat the water from local bores.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In early 2019, at a site near Kaljiti/Fregon, a new water source was found in a "palaeo-valley", where groundwater is held about 90 metres (300 ft) below the surface (existing sources being about 30 metres [100 ft] down).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Core drill samples have been dated at 5–10 million years old.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Pipes were temporarily capped, but elder Witjiti George said that he hoped the water could be used to support a cattle herd, helping to create jobs and an ongoing industry for isolated communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The new source could also provide much needed drinking water.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] APY Lands general manager Richard King said the origin of the water was yet to be established, but the water is pure, with low salinity.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Government experts were working with Flinders University and the CSIRO to learn more about the source.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In January 2020, the government of South Australia declared that due to the 2019–20 Australian bushfire season and drought, feral camels in large numbers were destroying infrastructure and putting families and communities in danger as they searched for water sources.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] They were also destroying native vegetation, contaminating water supplies and destroying cultural sites.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] On 8 January 2020 the South Australian Department for Environment and Water began a five-day cull of the camels, the first mass cull of camels in the area.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Professional shooters would kill between 4,000 and 5,000 (or up to 10,000) camels from helicopters, "...in accordance with the highest standards of animal welfare".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The APY is renowned for its artists, who are always well-represented in any exhibitions and awards for Indigenous Australian artists.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Nici Cumpston, artistic director of Tarnanthi Festival at Art Gallery of South Australia, regularly visits the APY art centres.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The **APY Art Centre Collective** is a group of ten Indigenous-owned and -governed enterprises which supports artists from across the Lands and helps to market their work.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The idea was born in 2013, when artists from seven remote art centres got together to look for ways to help the Anangu artists create a network around Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] It was initially funded from the proceeds of art sales only, but in July 2017 was registered as a public benevolent institution, and as of 2019 was receiving support from the Australia Council, federal and state governments.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] However the artists themselves manage the collective.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The individual art centres saw collaboration as a natural progression, because "We're telling the same story, and when we work together it makes us stronger"; in addition, exploitation by third parties is reduced.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The collective aims to create and investigate new markets for their work, increase income for each art centre and support their business development, and in addition support collaborative regional projects, such as the renowned Kulata Tjuta project, and the APY Photography initiative.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Seven art centres across the Lands support the work of more than 500 Anangu artists, from the oldest one, Ernabella Arts, to Iwantja Arts at Indulkana, whose residents include award-winning Vincent Namatjira.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] As well as the APY centres, Maruku Arts from Uluru, Tjanpi Desert Weavers based in Alice Springs, and Ara Iritja Aboriginal Corporation bring the number up to ten.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Artist Sally Scales (who was formerly the youngest person to have been chair of the APY Executive Board) has been involved with the Collective since 2017 and is as of 2021 a regional project coordinator.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The Collective has galleries in Darlinghurst, Sydney, and, since May 2019, a gallery and studio space on Light Square in Adelaide, known as **APY Gallery Adelaide**.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] The Adelaide studio will function as another working space, the first to be established off-Country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] An important aspect is that the artists are able to continue working when visiting healthcare facilities or family in Adelaide, with shuttle buses running between the centre and dialysis centre.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] Nearly 30% of 2019 gallery sales were made by overseas purchasers, and about 50% from the Eastern states of Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] About 84% of artwork sales (A$1.6 million as of July 2020) has been returned to the communities through the APY Art centres, which are the only source of income in most of these communities apart from the government.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In 2019, 17 APY artists were finalists in the Wynne Prize at the Art Gallery of New South Wales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In early April 2020, the Adelaide gallery had to close to the public, in line with restrictions imposed by the government owing to the COVID-19 pandemic in Australia, so the gallery went online.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In May 2020 it was announced that two of the gallery's resident painters, Sammy Lyons and Leah Brady, were finalists in the Telstra National Aboriginal & Torres Strait Islander Art Awards.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/apy-lands] In April 2021, a joint exhibition of the work of Sally Scales and her mother, Josephine Mick, *Irititja – Old, Kuwaritja – New, Ngali – Us (a generational story)*, was opened by prominent Sydney artist Ben Quilty.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Many of the constellations were given names based on their shapes, just as traditional western astronomy does, such as the Pleiades, Orion and the Milky Way, with others, such as Emu in the Sky, describes the dark patches rather than the points lit by the stars.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Contemporary Indigenous Australian art often references astronomical subjects and their related lore, such as the Seven Sisters.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] One of the earliest written records of Aboriginal astronomy was made by William Edward Stanbridge, an Englishman who emigrated to Australia in 1841 and befriended the local Boorong people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] A constellation used almost everywhere in Australian Aboriginal culture is the "Emu in the Sky", which consists of dark nebulae (opaque clouds of dust and gas in outer space) that are visible against the (centre and other sectors of the) Milky Way background.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Emu's head is the very dark Coalsack Nebula, next to the Southern Cross; the body and legs are that extension of the Great Rift trailing out to Scorpius.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In Ku-ring-gai Chase National Park, north of Sydney, are extensive rock engravings of the Guringai people who lived there, including representations of the creator-hero Daramulan and his emu-wife.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] An engraving near the Elvina Track shows an emu in the same pose and orientation as the Emu in the Sky constellation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] To the Wardaman, however, the Coalsack is the head of a lawman.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Bruce Pascoe's 2014 book *Dark Emu* takes its title from one of the Aboriginal names for the constellation, known as Gugurmin to the Wiradjuri people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In May 2020, the Royal Australian Mint launched a limited edition commemorative one-dollar coin, as the first in its "Star Dreaming" series celebrating Indigenous Australians' astrology.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu people of northern Australia say that the constellation of Orion, which they call Julpan (or Djulpan), is a canoe.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They tell the story of three brothers who went fishing, and one of them ate a sawfish that was forbidden under their law.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Seeing this, the Sun-woman, Walu, made a waterspout that carried him and his two brothers and their canoe up into the sky.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The three stars that line in the constellation's centre, which form Orion's Belt in Western mythology, are the three brothers; the Orion Nebula above them is the forbidden fish; and the bright stars Betelgeuse and Rigel are the bow and stern of the canoe.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] This is an example of astronomical legends underpinning the ethical and social codes that people use on Earth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Pleiades constellation figures in the Dreamings and songlines of several Aboriginal Australian peoples, usually referred to as the seven sisters.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The story also includes Warlpiri lands, the Tanami Desert of the Northern Territory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yamatji people of the Wajarri language group, of the Murchison region in Western Australia, call the sisters Nyarluwarri.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] When the constellation is close to the horizon as the sun is setting, the people know that it is the right time to harvest emu eggs, and they also use the brightness of the stars to predict seasonal rainfall.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the Kimberley region of Western Australia, the eagle hawk chases the seven sisters up into the sky, where they become the star cluster and he becomes the Southern Cross.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the Western Desert cultural bloc in central Australia, they are said to be seven sisters fleeing from the unwelcome attentions of a man represented by some of the stars in Orion, the hunter.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In these stories, the man is called Nyiru or Nirunja, and the Seven Sisters is songline known as *Kungkarangkalpa*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Museum of Contemporary Art Australia in Sydney holds a 2013 work by the Tjanpi Desert Weavers called *Minyma Punu Kungkarangkalpa* (Seven Sisters Tree Women).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In March 2013, senior desert dancers from the APY Lands (South Australia) in collaboration with the Australian National University's ARC Linkage and mounted by artistic director Wesley Enoch, performed *Kungkarangkalpa: The Seven Sisters Songline* on the shores of Lake Burley Griffin in Canberra.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the Warlpiri version of the story, the Napaljarri sisters are often represented carrying a man called Wardilyka, who is in love with the women.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] But the morning star, Jukurra-jukurra, a man from a different skin group and who is also in love with the sisters, chases them across the sky.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Each night they launch themselves into the sky, and each night he follows them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] This story is known as the *Napaljarri-warnu Jukurrpa*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The people of around Lake Eyre in South Australia tell how the ancestor male is prevented from capturing one of the seven sisters by a great flood.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Wirangu people of the west coast of South Australia have a creation story embodied in a songline of great significance based on the Pleiades.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the story, the hunter (the Orion constellation) is named Tgilby.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Tgilby, after falling in love with the seven sisters, known as Yugarilya, chases them out of the sky, onto and across the earth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] He chases them as the Yugarilya chase a snake, Dyunu.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Boonwurrung people of the Kulin nation of Victoria tell the Karatgurk story, which tells of how a crow robbed the seven sisters of their secret of how to make fire, thus bringing the skill to the people on earth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In another story, told by peoples of New South Wales, the seven sisters are beautiful women known as the Maya-Mayi, two of whom are kidnapped by a warrior, Warrumma, or Warunna.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They eventually escape by climbing a pine tree that continually grows up into the sky where they join their other sisters.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In 2017, a major exhibition entitled *Songlines: Tracking the Seven Sisters* was mounted at the National Museum of Australia, afterwards travelling to Berlin (2022) and Paris (2023).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In September 2020, the Royal Australian Mint issued its second commemorative one-dollar coin in its "Star Dreaming" series celebrating Indigenous Australians' astrology (see Emu in the sky above).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Kaurna people of the Adelaide Plains of South Australia called the (centre and other sectors of) the Milky Way *wodliparri* in the Kaurna language, meaning "house river".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They believed that Karrawirra Parri (the River Torrens) was a reflection of wodliparri.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu people believe that when they die, they are taken by a mystical canoe, *Larrpan*, to the spirit-island Baralku in the sky, where their camp-fires can be seen burning along the edge of the great river of the Milky Way.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The canoe is sent back to Earth as a shooting star, letting their family on Earth know that they have arrived safely in the spirit-land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Aboriginals also thought that god was the canoe.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Boorong people see in the Southern Cross a possum in a tree.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Many traditions have stories of a female Sun and a male Moon.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu say that Walu, the Sun-woman, lights a small fire each morning, which we see as the dawn.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] She paints herself with red ochre, some of which spills onto the clouds, creating the sunrise.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] She then lights a torch and carries it across the sky from east to west, creating daylight.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] At the end of her journey, as she descends from the sky, some of her ochre paints again rubs off onto the clouds, creating the sunset.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] She then puts out her torch, and throughout the night travels underground back to her starting camp in the east.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Other Aboriginal peoples of the Northern Territory call her Wuriupranili.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Other stories about the Sun involve Wala, Yhi, and Gnowee.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu tell that Ngalindi, the Moon-man, was once young and slim (the waxing Moon), but grew fat and lazy (the full Moon).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] His wives chopped bits off him with their axes (the waning Moon); to escape them he climbed a tall tree towards the Sun, but died from the wounds (the new Moon).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] After remaining dead for three days, he rose again to repeat the cycle, and continues doing so till this day.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Kuwema people in the Northern Territory say that he grows fat at each full Moon by devouring the spirits of those who disobey the tribal laws.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Another story by the Aboriginals of Cape York involves the making of a giant boomerang that is thrown into the sky and becomes the Moon.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] A story from Southern Victoria concerns a beautiful woman who is forced to live by herself in the sky after a number of scandalous affairs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Yolŋu also associated the Moon with the tides.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Warlpiri people explain a solar eclipse as being the Sun-woman being hidden by the Moon-man as he makes love to her.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] This explanation is shared by other groups, such as the Wirangu.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In the Ku-ring-gai Chase National Park there are a number of engravings showing a crescent shape, with sharp horns pointing down, and below it a drawing of a man in front of a woman.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] While the crescent shape has been assumed by most researchers to represent a boomerang, some argue that it is more easily interpreted as a solar eclipse, with the mythical man-and-woman explanation depicted below it.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The rising of Venus marks an important ceremony of the Yolŋu, who call it Barnumbirr ("Morning Star and Evening Star").
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They gather after sunset to await the rising of the planet.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The Dja Dja Wurrung call Jupiter "Bunjil's campfire".
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The planet features in the Dja Dja Wurrung Aboriginal Clans Corporation logo, as a symbol of the Creator Spirit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] This is the only definitive indigenous record of Eta Carinae's outburst identified in the literature to date.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Aboriginal calendars tend to differ from European calendars: many groups in northern Australia use a calendar with six seasons, and some groups mark the seasons by the stars which are visible during them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] For the Pitjantjatjara, for example, the rising of the Pleiades at dawn (in May) marks the start of winter.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] It is not known to what extent Aboriginal people were interested in the precise motion of the sun, moon, planets or stars.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] However, it likely that some of the stone arrangements in Victoria such as Wurdi Youang near Little River, Victoria, may have been used to predict and confirm the equinoxes and/or solstices.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] The arrangement is aligned with the setting sun at the solstices and equinox, but its age is unknown.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] There are rock engravings by the Nganguraku people at Ngaut Ngaut which, according to oral tradition, represent lunar cycles.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Most of their culture (including their language) has been lost because of the banning of such things by Christian missionaries before 1913.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Stories enrich a custom-linked calendar whereby the heliacal rising or setting of stars or constellations indicates to Aboriginal Australians when it is time to move to a new place and/or look for a new food source.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] For example, the Boorong people in Victoria know that when *the Malleefowl* (Lyra) disappears in October, to "sit with the Sun", it is time to start gathering her eggs on Earth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Other groups know that when Orion first appears in the sky, the dingo puppies are about to be born.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] When Scorpius appears, the Yolŋu know that the Macassan fisherman would soon arrive to fish for trepang.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] A great deal of contemporary Aboriginal art has an astronomical theme, reflecting the astronomical elements of the artists' cultures.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Prominent examples are Gulumbu Yunupingu, Bill Yidumduma Harney, and Nami Maymuru, all of whom have won awards or been finalists in the Telstra Indigenous Art Awards.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] In 2009 an exhibition of Indigenous Astronomical Art from WA, named "Ilgarijiri", was launched at AIATSIS in Canberra in conjunction with a Symposium on Aboriginal Astronomy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Other contemporary painters include the daughters of the late Clifford Possum Tjapaltjarri, who have the seven sisters as one of their Dreamings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] Gabriella Possum and Michelle Possum paint the Seven Sisters Dreaming in their paintings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/australian-aboriginal-astronomy] They inherited this Dreaming through their maternal line.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:australian-aboriginal-astronomy/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
